sql:
SELECT election_id, COUNT(ballot_id) AS number_of_absentee_ballots
FROM absentee_ballots
GROUP BY election_id;

SELECT AVG(turnout_percentage) AS average_turnout
FROM voter_turnout AS T1
INNER JOIN precincts AS T2 ON T1.precinct_id = T2.precinct_id;

external_knowledge:
- "Middle-aged" refers to voters between the ages of 18 and 65;
- "Middle-income" refers to voters with an income level classified as 'Middle';
- "Supporting the winning parties" means the voters' party affiliation matches that of the winning candidates.

- The city of interest has city_id = 1;
- The query focuses on demographic and turnout statistics within this specific city;
- The term "older" in the question refers to the average age being higher than the overall average age of the city;
- The term "higher total votes cast" means the precinct has the maximum total votes cast among all precincts in the city.

sql:
SELECT AVG(turnout_percentage) AS average_turnout
FROM voter_turnout
WHERE total_registered > 1000;

SELECT AVG(candidate_count) AS avg_candidates_per_party
FROM (
  SELECT party_affiliation, COUNT(candidate_id) AS candidate_count
  FROM candidates
  GROUP BY party_affiliation
);

SELECT COUNT(ballot_id) AS total_received_ballots
FROM absentee_ballots
WHERE status = 'Received';

external_knowledge:
- "leading trio" refers to the top 3 candidates;
- "captured the hearts of the voters" refers to the candidates with the highest vote percentages;
- "grand electoral theater" is a metaphor for the election process.

- "Winning candidate" refers to the candidate with the highest number of votes in a precinct;
- "Voter turnout" is calculated as the total votes cast divided by the total registered voters in a precinct;
- "Greater than 70%" indicates that more than 70% of registered voters in the precinct cast their votes.

- "bustling metropolises" refers to cities with a population greater than 100,000;
- "vibrant community" indicates a significant proportion of young adults and adults (60% or more) among the voting population;
- "gap between the highest and lowest voter turnout percentages" is the difference between the maximum and minimum voter turnout percentages for each city;
- "young adults" are voters between the ages of 18 and 30;
- "adults" are voters between the ages of 31 and 50.

- "Beacons of civic engagement" refers to precincts with the highest voter turnout;
- "Shone the brightest" indicates the highest performance in voter turnout;
- "Recent election" refers to the election with `election_id = 1`.

- 'The grand theatrical performance of democracy' refers to the election process;
- 'Curtain rise on more than a thousand votes' means the total votes cast in the city exceed 1000;
- 'Crowned the victor' refers to the winning candidate in the election.

- "Ward%" refers to ward names that start with "Ward";
- "Population exceeding 2000" means the city has more than 2000 inhabitants;
- "Citizens' enthusiasm for voting" is measured by the average voter turnout percentage;
- "Total voters" refers to the sum of all registered voters in the precincts of these cities.

- "Voter turnout" is the percentage of registered voters who cast a ballot in an election;
- "City average turnout" is the average voter turnout across all precincts in a city;
- "Total votes cast" refers to the number of votes recorded in a precinct during an election;
- "Average total votes" is the mean number of votes cast across all precincts.

- "beacons of civic engagement" refers to cities and states with the highest voter turnout;
- "wards see the highest voter turnout" refers to the precincts within wards that have the highest voter turnout percentage;
- "champions of the ballot" refers to the candidates who received the most votes in those precincts.

- 'Young Adults' refer to voters aged 18-29;
- 'Adults' refer to voters aged 30-44;
- 'Middle-Aged Adults' refer to voters aged 45-64;
- 'Senior Citizens' refer to voters aged 65 and above.

